Also, I paste Arvind's comments from JIRA to here, you may need to take a look and feedback:

> Thanks for working on this defect. Could you share how these new options ( la, lq, key ) will be used ?
> For the problem seen when one of the zookeeper nodes/process among the quorum is down, I think we need to pass in the quorum information to the "-server" option. Currently we pick one server and port and pass that. With the change if we invoke "dcs zkcli" it should default to showing all servers of the quorum like hbase zkcli does:
> 
> hbase zkcli
> Connecting to wmstesting-1.novalocal:2181,wmstesting-3.novalocal:2181,wmstesting-2.novalocal:2181...
> bin/dcs zkcli
> Connecting to wmstesting-1.novalocal:2181
> If you do make this change to -server, then note that dcscheck and dcsstart will need to be modified to pick the correct row/column.
> Other suggestion - we could eliminate the configuration in dcs-site.xml by utilizing the following env variables that get set in a cluster environment:
> [trafodion@wmstesting-1 dcs-2.2.0]$ env|grep ZOO
> ZOOKEEPER=zookeeper
> ZOO_PORT_NODES=wmstesting-2.novalocal:2181,wmstesting-1.novalocal:2181,wmstesting-3.novalocal:2181
> ZOOKEEPER_PORT=2181
> ZOOKEEPER_NODES=wmstesting-3.novalocal,wmstesting-1.novalocal,wmstesting-2.novalocal

It is not clear what is the intent of moving ExpLobInterfaceInit method from fixup to work method. By moving to the work method, we would be setting up the threads for every execution. This increases the probability of having more zombie threads

Removed init calls from fixup since there is chance of re-fixups. There were cleanup calls in some cases in work method, in these cases, matched the init call in work method. In case of hdfsscan.cpp, the cleanup call is in destructor, in this case moved the init to constructor of the tcb.  
I shall move the init and cleanup to tcb constructor/destructor.

Much of this code is a copy of the PostgreSQL source code. You cannot strip off the PostgreSQL license header and copyright from these files. I'm not quite sure how this should be handled, but my guess would be that you need to leave the PostgreSQL license header in the file and add the Apache License header as well. Also, you may need to add an entry to the RAT_README file in the top-level directory. See also http://www.apache.org/legal/resolved.html, this states that it is ok to include PostgreSQL code in an Apache project. Maybe @gtapper, our new Release Manager, can help you with the details. Our previous release manager, @robertamarton, has a lot of experience with this.

Just another quick comment: It's not true that Trafodion didn't support double as an output type, these "addColumn" methods are just convenience functions to avoid the more complicated way of adding a column. So, if you need to add a more complex data type, you can just create a TypeInfo and a ColumnInfo and then call the AddColumn() method.
